In JavaScript, increment (++) and decrement (--) operators are used to increase or decrease a numeric value by 1. They're simple but powerful tools, especially in loops and counters.

ðŸ”¼ Increment Operator (++)
Adds 1 to the value of a variable.

Postfix (x++): Returns the value before incrementing.

Prefix (++x): Returns the value after incrementing.

javascript
let x = 5;
console.log(x++); // 5 (then x becomes 6)
console.log(++x); // 7 (x is incremented first)







ðŸ”½ Decrement Operator (--)
Subtracts 1 from the value of a variable.

Postfix (x--): Returns the value before decrementing.

Prefix (--x): Returns the value after decrementing.

javascript
let y = 10;
console.log(y--); // 10 (then y becomes 9)
console.log(--y); // 8 (y is decremented first)
ðŸ§  Use Cases
Loop counters (for, while)

Toggling values

Tracking scores or steps